    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-04-22T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-04-22T18:00:00-05:00" n="780"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d780">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/4–2354: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-04-23T00:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 23, 1954—midnight.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 10.” Eyes only Acting Secretary. At Quai
                    d’Orsay dinner tonight following developed through bilateral talks: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_PR1">Pleven</persName> informed me that
                            “cease-fire” referred to in <persName corresp="#p_NGH1"
                                >Navarre</persName>’s message<note n="1" xml:id="d780fn1">Regarding
                                the message from General <persName corresp="#p_NGH1"
                                    >Navarre</persName>, see telegram <gloss target="#t_Dulte1"
                                    >Dulte</gloss> 7, Apr. 23, <ref target="#pg_1374">p.
                                1374</ref>.</note> would in his opinion not be local, but general
                            throughout Indochina.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> expressed to me grave doubts
                            that Britain would cooperate in any active fighting to save Indochina.
                            He expressed fear that United States intervention might initiate World
                            War Three and urged we should take no such action without prior
                            consultation. He expressed view that there should be prompt military
                            consultations in Washington, including representatives of Thailand to
                            make plans to endeavor hold situation if Indochina lost. He said he did
                            not believe that <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName> cable
                            to President<note n="2" xml:id="d780fn2">Regarding the message from
                                Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName> to
                                President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>, see
                                    <ref target="#d774fn3">footnote 3, p. 1367</ref>.</note> was
                            primarily related to Indochina situation.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_BG1">Bidault</persName> expressed to <persName
                                corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> his belief that if United States
                            participated to help save Dien Bien Phu and if this help proved
                            inadequate for that purpose, under these circumstances, French would as
                            matter of honor go on fighting. However, he expressed to me the view
                            that assuming Dien Bien Phu fell without United States intervention, he
                            saw no hope of any French reaction, other than acceptance of defeat and
                            probably leftwing government which would hold office on sufferance of
                            Communists, although probably without open Communist
                            participation.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>
                            <persName corresp="#p_GGAM1">Gruenther</persName> expressed view he had
                            never seen French morale so low.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>There seems to be some possibility that a new formula can be found to
                            satisfy Mollet<note n="3" xml:id="d780fn3">
                                <persName>Guy Mollet</persName>, Secretary-General of the French
                                Socialist Party.</note> regarding <gloss target="#t_EDC1"
                                >EDC</gloss>. However, this calculation on basis of present
                            political situation and does not take account of repercussions which
                            could come from Indochina.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
